.SH NAME
Linux::Event::Watcher \- Mutable readiness watcher handle for Linux::Event::Reactor
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 6
\&  my $watcher = $loop\->watch(
\&    $fh,
\&    read => sub ($loop, $fh, $watcher) {
\&      ...
\&  use v5.36;
\&  use Linux::Event;
\&
\&  my $loop = Linux::Event\->new( model => \*(Aqreactor\*(Aq );
\&
\&  my $w = $loop\->watch($fh,
\&    read => sub ($loop, $fh, $w) {
\&      my $buf;
\&      my $n = sysread($fh, $buf, 8192);
\&
\&      if (!defined $n || $n == 0) {
\&        $w\->cancel;
\&        close $fh;
\&        return;
\&      }
\&
\&      # ... handle $buf ...
\&    },
\&
\&    write => sub ($loop, $fh, $w) {
\&      # fd became writable
\&      $w\->disable_write; # typical: only enable when you actually have pending output
\&    },
\&
\&    error => sub ($loop, $fh, $w) {
\&      # error readiness reported (see DISPATCH SEMANTICS)
\&      $w\->cancel;
\&      close $fh;
\&    },
\&  );
\&
\&  $watcher\->disable_read;
\&  $watcher\->enable_read;
\&  $watcher\->cancel;
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
\&\f(CW\*(C`Linux::Event::Watcher\*(C'\fR is the lightweight handle returned by
"watch" in Linux::Event::Reactor. It stores the current callbacks, enablement
flags, filehandle metadata, and a user data slot.
.PP
The watcher does not own backend policy. Methods that change interest state
simply delegate back into the loop.
